Yes, you can assign a user a random number between 1 and 100 using Kameleoon's Pseudo Random Number Generator (PRNG) capabilities. Kameleoon's SDKs provide access to a random floating-point number between 0 and 1 (similar to JavaScript's Math.random). You can easily scale this to your desired range.

For example, in JavaScript or TypeScript, you can do the following:

```js
// Generate a random integer between 1 and 100
const randomNumber = Math.floor(Math.random() * 100) + 1;
```

If you are using Kameleoon's SDK and want to use a custom PRNG, you can implement it as shown in the documentation:

```js
class MyPRNG {
  getRandomNumber() {
    // Returns a random floating point number between 0 and 1
    return Math.random();
  }
}

// Use this PRNG in your KameleoonClient initialization if needed
const client = createClient({
  siteCode: 'my_site_code',
  externals: {
    prng: new MyPRNG(),
  },
});
```

You can then use the random number generator to assign a value between 1 and 100 as shown above.

For more details, see:
- Pseudo Random Number Generator (Web SDK): https://docs.kameleoon.com/developer-docs/sdks/web-sdks/react-js-sdk#pseudo-random-number-generator
- Pseudo Random Number Generator (React Native SDK): https://docs.kameleoon.com/developer-docs/sdks/mobile-sdks/react-native-sdk#pseudo-random-number-generator

